                <h3>Student Privacy Laws: What District & School Administrators Need To Know</h3>
                <p>Due to the increased use of technology in schools, student data privacy has been a major concern in the United States in recent years. Education officials are facing an urgent need to traverse complicated federal, state, and local privacy rules.</p>
                
                <h3>The Big Three Privacy Laws for Student Data</h3>
                <div class="card-container">
                    <div class="card">
                        <h3>FERPA</h3>
                        <p>Family Educational Rights and Privacy Act (1974) - Protects the privacy of student education records</p>
                    </div>
                    <div class="card">
                        <h3>COPPA</h3>
                        <p>Children's Online Privacy Protection Act (1998) - Protects children under 13 online</p>
                    </div>
                    <div class="card">
                        <h3>GDPR</h3>
                        <p>General Data Protection Regulation (2018) - EU regulation protecting personal data</p>
                    </div>
                </div>
                
                <h3>Family Educational Rights and Privacy Act (FERPA)</h3>
                <p>FERPA, created in 1974 by the United States Department of Education, is a federal statute that gives parents and students aged 18 and above the right to examine educational records. It applies to both paper and electronic documents, including directory information and de-identified data.</p>
                
                <h3>Children's Online Privacy Protection Act (COPPA)</h3>
                <p>COPPA was implemented in 1998 by the Federal Trade Commission (FTC), to protect children under the age of 13 online privacy. This law says, website and online service operators who solicit or address PII of children under the age of 13, need to be authorized by parents/guardian.</p>
                
                <h3>General Data Protection Regulation (GDPR)</h3>
                <p>The General Data Protection Regulation (GDPR) is a comprehensive European Union law that came into force in May 2018 to protect the privacy and personal information of EU residents. It implements a stringent regime under which organizations worldwide must collect, process, store, and protect such information.</p>
